
6. Modules and Mixins {#_idParaDest-168}
=====================

::: {#_idContainer264 .Content}
:::

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
Overview

By the end of the chapter, you will be able to implement modules within
the Ruby object model; add instance methods by including a module into a
class; add class methods by extending a class with a module; create a
namespace with a module; distinguish between prepending modules into
classes and including and extending them and use modules to address
multiple inheritance in Ruby.


Introduction {#_idParaDest-169}
============

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
In the previous chapter, we learned about the basics of object-oriented
programming using Ruby. We learned that classes serve as templates for
objects. We also learned that classes can also serve as templates for
other classes by using the mechanism of inheritance. However, there may
be situations where we might have to share code among different classes
that don\'t really fit into an inheritance architecture. For example, we
could be designing a reality simulator. In the previous chapter, we
talked about how cars have four wheels, bicycles have two wheels, and
boats have no wheels, but they still fall under the \"Vehicles\" class.
Imagine that we had previously been tasked with modeling houses or
places to live, which we can easily do using classes. Now we are tasked
with modeling a mobile home or RV, which serves as both a vehicle and a
home.

In other object-oriented languages, this problem is solved with a
concept known as \"multiple inheritance\". For instance, in C++, a class
could inherit from more than one base class. Ruby does not support
multiple inheritance. Instead, Ruby solves this code reusability problem
using the concept of modules.

Modules provide a way to conveniently wrap code in a way that can be
shared among many other pieces of code. Modules can be included,
extended, and prepended into other code. Modules can also serve as a way
to namespace code. The nuances of each of these approaches require a bit
more discussion of the Ruby object model. We\'ll be talking about the
Ruby object model. This will give us a foundation for understanding how
modules work so we can then learn about `extend`{.literal} and
`prepend`{.literal} and how and when to use them. We will also study the
mixin characteristic of modules. The idea of mixins essentially refers
to the property of multiple modules being used by a class to improve
code functionality and provide multiple inheritance in Ruby.

Let\'s begin with the `include`{.literal} functionality of modules.


Including Modules {#_idParaDest-170}
=================

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
Modules, in their simplest definition, are a way to wrap code into a
bundle so the code can be reused within other code without needing to be
duplicated.

This definition sounds very similar to that of a Ruby class.
Specifically, what makes a Ruby module distinct is that it cannot be
instantiated into an object like a class. It can, however, be included
in a class so the methods and variables defined in the module are
accessible by the class. This refers to the mixin property of modules.
Also, the methods and variables in a class can also be accessible to the
code in the module. Essentially, when a module is included in a class,
Ruby treats that code as if it were written right into that class. All
the previous concepts we learned about classes and inheritance still
apply to the module code when called.

For instance, if you call a module method from inside a class, that
module method calls `super`{.literal} and it will call the
`super`{.literal} class method of the class that the module was included
in. This will be made clearer through the following example.

Let\'s assume we have a `User`{.literal} class in which every user has a
postal address. It can be realized as shown in the following code block:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class User
  attr_accessor :address_line1, :address_line2, :city, :state, :postal_code, :country
  def mailing_label
    label = []
    label << address_line1
    label << address_line2
    label << "#{city}, #{state} #{postal_code}"
    label << country
    label.join("\n")
  end
end
```
:::

Now, say we need to add the concept of buildings to our application.
Buildings should also have addresses associated with them. We don\'t
want to repeat ourselves and yet we still want to make sure that our
`User`{.literal} class and `Building`{.literal} class both have this
same functionality. We could theoretically do this with inheritance, but
it doesn\'t really make sense to subclass the `User`{.literal} class and
`Building`{.literal} class from an `Address`{.literal} class as they
aren\'t \"types\" of addresses. Instead, we will wrap this functionality
in a module and include it in both classes.

Look at the following code:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module Address
  attr_accessor :address_line1, :address_line2, :city, :state, :postal_code, :country 
  def mailing_label
    label = []
    label << @address_line1
    label << @address_line2
    label << "#{@city}, #{@state} #{@postal_code}"
    label << @country
    label.join("\n")
  end
end
class User
  include Address
end
class Building
  include Address
end
```
:::

As we can see, modules are declared using the `module`{.literal}
keyword, and they are included in classes using the `include`{.literal}
keyword. Defining methods is done similarly as they are inside a class
definition.

The preceding code is using instance variables in the module to
demonstrate a point but could also use the accessor methods created by
`attr_accessor`{.literal}.

This is a great way of sharing code. It is a clean way to reuse code. If
any new models are necessary in the future and they need an address, we
basically get it for free by simply including the module. This is the
power of Ruby and object-oriented programming in action.

Let\'s dive deeper into how this works by working with some objects.

Consider the following code example:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
u = User.new
b = Building.new
u.address_line1 = "123 Main Street"
b.address_line1 = "987 Broadway"
puts u.address_line1
puts b.address_line1
puts u.instance_variable_get("@address_line1")
puts u.instance_variable_get("@address_line1").object_id
puts b.instance_variable_get("@address_line1")
puts b.instance_variable_get("@address_line1").object_id
```
:::

The output would show up as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer265 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.1: Output after including modules ](3_files/C14197_06_01.jpg)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.1: Output after including modules

There is an important point in the preceding output. While the module is
the same code and, in essence, referencing an instance variable with the
same name, it is, indeed, a completely different object instance. This
is demonstrated by grabbing the instance variable and outputting the
`object_id`{.literal} attribute of that object. The
`object_id`{.literal} attribute on any object is a unique ID maintained
by Ruby. You can think of this as Ruby copying and pasting the module
code into the class that we included the module in. So, any variables
and code that are included are actually separate across different
classes that include them.

Exercise 6.01: Controlling the Operations of Services in an Application {#_idParaDest-171}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we will extend the `Service`{.literal} class with a
module called `Logger`{.literal} and take a look at how the inclusion of
the module modifies the inner workings of our application.

Note

The `Logger`{.literal} module is a tool used for debugging in Ruby. We
will be looking at the `Logger`{.literal} module in more detail in
*Chapter 8*, *Debugging with Ruby*.

The following steps will help you complete the exercise:

1.  Open up a new file, `Exercise6.01.rb`{.literal}.

2.  Define the `Logger`{.literal} module:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module Logger
      def log_message(level, message)
        File.open("ServiceLogs.txt", "a") do |f|
            f.write "#{level}: #{message}\n"
        end
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

3.  Now we can define the `Service`{.literal} class:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class Service
      include Logger
      def stop_service(service_name)
        log_message :info, "Stopping service: #{service_name}"
        sleep 3
        log_message :info, "The service: #{service_name} was stopped!"
      end
      def start_service(service_name)
        log_message :inf, "Starting the service: #{service_name}"
        sleep 2
        log_message :info, "The service: #{service_name} was started!"
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

4.  Now we instantiate the class and call the functions on the service
    called `Windows Update`{.literal}:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    TestService = Service.new
    TestService.stop_service("Windows Update")
    TestService.start_service("Windows Update")
    ```
    :::

5.  Invoke the code with `ruby Exercise6.01.rb`{.literal}.

    The contents of the `ServiceLogs.txt`{.literal} file should be as
    follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer266 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.2: Service logs output ](3_files/C14197_06_02.jpg)
    :::

Figure 6.2: Service logs output

Thus, we have successfully used the `Logger`{.literal} module to
generate a service update on an application.

Inheritance with Module Methods {#_idParaDest-172}
-------------------------------

When we include a module in a class, we are basically copying the
instance methods into a class. This is a very important point in
understanding modules. `include`{.literal} brings in the methods of a
module into a class as instance methods.Because they are brought in as
instance methods, all of the concepts that we learned about in the
previous chapter about object-oriented programming and inheritance will
apply to these methods.

Consider the following code block:

inheritancewithmodulemethods.rb 

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
1  module Address
2    attr_accessor :address_line1, :address_line2, :city, :state,:postal_code, :country 
3  
4    def region
5      return nil if country.nil? || country == ""
6      case country
7      when "United States", "Canada", "Mexico"
8         "North America"
9      else
10         "Global"
11     end
12   end
13 end
14 
```
:::

<https://packt.live/322sM7Y>

Here, we\'ve amended our `Address`{.literal} module to include a
`region`{.literal} method. We\'ve also created a `Department`{.literal}
class and subclassed `User`{.literal} to create an `Employee`{.literal}
class that has a `Department`{.literal} attribute. The
`Employee`{.literal} class has implemented its own `region`{.literal}
method and is delegating `region`{.literal} to the department. If the
department does not have a region, it calls `super`{.literal}, which
will, in effect, call the original `Address`{.literal} class\'s method,
which was included in the `User`{.literal} class. Let\'s see this on the
console:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
e = Employee.new
e.region
e.country = "Mexico"
e.region
e.department = Department.new
e.region
e.department.country = "England"
e.region
```
:::

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer267 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.3: Output for subclass overriding a method
](3_files/C14197_06_03.jpg)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.3: Output for subclass overriding a method

Our subclass has overridden a method defined in the module and is able
to call `super`{.literal} to that method if necessary.

[]{#_idTextAnchor179}

Inclusion Ordering {#_idParaDest-173}
------------------

The \"copying and pasting\" that\'s happening occurs at runtime, so the
order of the inclusion of modules is important. Let\'s examine a case in
which two modules have a method called `email`{.literal}. One module
returns a formatted email address, and the other sends an email:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module EmailFormatter
  def email
    "#{first_name}.#{last_name}@#{domain}"
  end
end
module EmailSender
  def email(msg, sender, recipient)
    # contrived implementation for now
    puts "Delivering email to #{recipient} from #{sender} with message: #{msg}"
 end
end
class User
  attr_accessor :first_name, :last_name, :domain
  include EmailFormatter
  include EmailSender
end
u = User.new
u.first_name = "John"
u.last_name = "Smith"
u.domain = "example.com"
puts u.email
```
:::

The output will be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer268 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.4: Output error for inclusion ordering
](3_files/C14197_06_04.jpg)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.4: Output error for inclusion ordering

Here, we can see that the implementation from the
`EmailSender`{.literal} module is being called. Let\'s reverse it.
Please restart IRB for this to work properly:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class User
  attr_accessor :first_name, :last_name, :domain
  include EmailSender
  include EmailFormatter
end
u = User.new
u.first_name = "John"
u.last_name = "Smith"
u.domain = "example.com"
puts u.email
```
:::

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer269 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.5: Output after changing the order
](3_files/C14197_06_05.jpg)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.5: Output after changing the order

And now the implementation we expected is being called. The second
module would have done better to call its `send_email`{.literal} method
instead of just the generic `email`{.literal} name.

Note

Avoid using methods names that are generic and may be used in other
modules or classes. This will help to avoid name conflicts, especially
if the module you are writing is intended to be used for a large
application or will be publicly released.

Inclusion ordering is also important if the module contains class
methods that can be called at the class level. You won\'t be able to
call a class-level method that the module provides if the module has not
yet been included. We\'ll take a look at this in the next section, which
discusses adding class methods with modules using `extend`{.literal}.


extend {#_idParaDest-174}
======

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
In the previous section, we learned about including methods from a
module for instances of a class using the `include`{.literal} keyword.
Modules can also be used to add class methods to a class. This can be
accomplished by using the `extend`{.literal} keyword.

Consider the following example:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module HelperMethods
  def attributes_for_json
    [:id, :name, :created_at]
  end
end
class User
  extend HelperMethods
end
class Company
  extend HelperMethods
end
irb(main):014:0> User.attributes_for_json
=> [:id, :name, :created_at]
irb(main):015:0> Company.attributes_for_json
=> [:id, :name, :created_at]
```
:::

Here, we\'ve defined a module called `HelperMethods`{.literal}, which
defines a single method called `attributes_for_json`{.literal}. The
intention is that these are a common set of attributes that will be used
to convert objects into JSON. Because these attributes are global, in
the sense that they apply to all objects, this method should be defined
as a class method.

You can see, though, that in the module, the method is just defined as a
straightforward method. There is no `self.`{.literal} that precedes it.
When the module is extended inside of a class, all of the methods that
are defined as basic methods get extended into the class, meaning that
they are added as class methods.

When working with modules, it\'s important to consider how the methods
are defined inside the module. This information, along with how you want
the methods to be defined, will inform whether you `include`{.literal}
the module or `extend`{.literal} it.

There is nothing stopping you from including the preceding module as
follows (restart IRB for this chapter):

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class User
  include HelperMethods
end
class Company
  include HelperMethods
end
```
:::

However, now these methods are defined as instance methods:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
irb(main):013:0> User.attributes_for_json
Traceback (most recent call last):
    2: from /Users/peter/.rbenv/versions/2.5.1/bin/irb:11:in `<main>'
    1: from (irb):13
NoMethodError (undefined method `attributes_for_json' for User:Class)
irb(main):014:0> User.new.attributes_for_json
=> [:id, :name, :created_at]
```
:::

Module authors will usually include in their `README`{.literal} file or
documentation as to how their module should be used by other developers.

Often, sophisticated modules add both class methods and instance
methods. In the following exercise, we\'ll take a look at a couple of
approaches.

[]{#_idTextAnchor181}

Exercise 6.02: Extending Your Modules with Class and Instance Methods {#_idParaDest-175}
---------------------------------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we will be creating a user module that implements the
`User`{.literal} class and instance methods to display the name and
email address of an individual. We will be using the
`HelperMethods`{.literal} module extensively to map the hashes for all
the variables. The following steps will help you to complete the
exercise:

1.  Define a `HelperMethods`{.literal} module that outputs a hash map of
    all the instance variables using the `inject`{.literal} method:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module HelperMethods
      def to_hash
        self.instance_variables.inject({}) do |map, iv|
            map[iv] = self.instance_variable_get(iv) 
            map
      end
     end
    end
    ```
    :::

2.  Define a `User`{.literal} class with `attr_accessors`{.literal}:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class User
      include HelperMethods
      attr_accessor :id, :name, :email
    end
    ```
    :::

3.  Test the `to_hash`{.literal} method on variables:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    u = User.new
    u.id = 1
    u.name = "Bob"
    u.email = "bob@example.com"
    u.to_hash
    ```
    :::

    The output will be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer270 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.6: Output for the hash method on variables
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

    Figure 6.6: Output for the hash method on variables

4.  Next, we create a submodule within the `HelperMethods`{.literal}
    module to contain the class methods:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module HelperMethods
      def to_hash
        self.instance_variables.inject({}) do |map, iv|
            map[iv] = self.instance_variable_get(iv) 
            map
      end
    end
      module ClassMethods
        def attributes_for_json
            [:name, :email]
        end
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    The intention here is to only allow some attributes to be output in
    the `to_hash`{.literal} method.

5.  Amend the `to_hash`{.literal} method to only use the attributes
    allowed by the class method:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module HelperMethods
      def to_hash
        formatted_class_attributes = self.class.attributes_for_json.map{|attr| "@#{attr}".to_sym}
        filtered_ivars = self.instance_variables & formatted_class_attributes
        filtered_ivars.inject({}) do |map, iv|
            map[iv] = self.instance_variable_get(iv) 
            map
      end
    end
    module ClassMethods
      def attributes_for_json
        [:name, :email]
      end
    end
    end
    ```
    :::

    We use `&`{.literal} to get the set intersection of two arrays. In
    other words, we\'re filtering for elements that exist in both
    arrays.

6.  Amend the `User`{.literal} class to include the instance methods,
    and extend the `ClassMethods`{.literal} submodule:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class User
      include HelperMethods
      extend HelperMethods::ClassMethods
      attr_accessor :id, :name, :email
    end
    ```
    :::

7.  Let\'s now test our `User`{.literal} module:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    u = User.new
    u.id = 1
    u.name = "Bob"
    u.email = "bob@example.com"
    u.to_hash
    ```
    :::

    The output should be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer271 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.7: Output for extending classes
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

Figure 6.7: Output for extending classes

And we\'re in business. We wrote a module that has both instance methods
and class methods available. Our `to_hash`{.literal} instance method
brought in by the module calls the class method. However, in the current
form, our client code, the `User`{.literal} class, has to both
`include`{.literal} and `extend`{.literal} the submodule. This is a bit
verbose and since our instance methods require the class method to be
there, it would be nice if, as module authors, we didn\'t leave it up to
other developers to write both lines of `include`{.literal} and
`extend`{.literal}.

Luckily, Ruby provides a way for us to detect when a module has been
included, and so we can write code to automatically extend the class
methods for us. Let\'s learn about this in the next section.

[]{#_idTextAnchor182}

Module Callbacks {#_idParaDest-176}
----------------

Callbacks, in general, are an architectural paradigm where a method or
function is \"called back\" to act upon some life cycle event. Web
frameworks have callbacks to allow code to be called before and/or after
a web request is processed. Database frameworks usually have callbacks
to call code before a record is created, updated, or deleted. You can
even think of the standard `initialize`{.literal} method as a callback
because Ruby is \"calling back\" to this method when an object is
created. Callbacks allow developers to \"hook into\" those life cycle
events and execute any code they wish.

In Ruby, there are a number of different types of callbacks to hook into
Ruby object\'s life cycle events, but here we\'re going to focus on
module callbacks. Ruby triggers a callback when a module has been either
included or extended. This ability gives rise

to a massively useful paradigm, as we will see later. But first, let\'s
see each callback in action.

[]{#_idTextAnchor183}

Exercise 6.03: Using Module Functions to Extend Classes {#_idParaDest-177}
-------------------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we will extend the `Facebook`{.literal} class with two
functions from the `ApiWrapper`{.literal} module, which are called
`send_message`{.literal} and `new_post`{.literal}:

1.  Create a new file, `Exercise6.03.rb`{.literal}.

2.  Define the `ApiWrapper`{.literal} module with the
    `send_message`{.literal} and `new_post`{.literal} functions:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module ApiWrapper
      def send_message(from, to, message)
        puts "Hi #{to}, I wanna say #{message}"
      end
      def new_post(from, title, description)
        puts "This is a post from #{from}, with title: #{title} and #{description}"
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

3.  Define the `Facebook`{.literal} class. We will extend
    `ApiWrapper`{.literal} within this class:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class Facebook
      extend ApiWrapper
    end
    ```
    :::

    Note

    Read more about Ruby life cycle callbacks here:
    <https://packt.live/35ts4D4>.

4.  Add testing code to the file:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    Facebook.send_message("Packt","Students","thank you!")
    Facebook.new_post("Author","Extending your classes","Extend imports functions from modules as class methods!")
    ```
    :::

5.  Invoke the test code with `ruby Exercise6.03.rb`{.literal}. The
    output will be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer272 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.8: Output for the Facebook class extension
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.8: Output for the Facebook class extension

We have successfully extended the class functionality using module
functions.

The `include`{.literal} keyword extends the namespace of a specific
class or module with extra functionality. Consider the following
example:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module SpyModule
  def self.included(base_class)
    puts "I've been included into: #{base_class}"
  end
end
class User
  include SpyModule
end
```
:::

Here, we\'ve defined our `SpyModule`{.literal} module, which has a
`self.included`{.literal} method, which takes an argument of the base
class. There are a few things to point out here:

-   The `included`{.literal} method callback is defined with
    `self.`{.literal} in front of it. This is known as a module method,
    and we will cover it in the next chapter.
-   The `base_class`{.literal} argument can be called anything. However,
    it will always represent the class that did the including of the
    module.
-   The `included`{.literal} method is called as soon as the class
    definition is loaded. Since class definitions are usually loaded
    earlier on in program execution, it makes it for an ideal time to
    further modify class definitions within the module.

Understanding class loading is a complex topic, especially when using a
framework such as Ruby on Rails. For the purposes of this book, we can
consider that all class loading will be done ahead of all program
execution; however, it should be noted that, in reality, class loading
is much more dynamic and can occur anywhere in program execution, even
near the end.

[]{#_idTextAnchor184}

Importing Modules as Class Methods using Extended {#_idParaDest-178}
-------------------------------------------------

The `extended`{.literal} callback works identically to the
`included`{.literal} callback. Look at the

following example:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module SpyModule
  def self.extended(base_class)
    puts "I've been extended into: #{base_class}"
  end
end
class User
  extend SpyModule
end
```
:::

In the preceding code, we have defined the `SpyModule`{.literal} module,
which defines the `self.extended`{.literal} method. This method, in
turn, takes the argument of `base_class`{.literal}.

[]{#_idTextAnchor185}

Combining include and extend {#_idParaDest-179}
----------------------------

As we saw in the previous exercise, module authors usually want to add
both instance and class methods. Module authors also want to make it
convenient and less error-prone for client code to leverage their
module. We can refactor the code from the previous exercise, so that
client code can simply `include`{.literal} our module, and then our
module takes care of everything else. The magic is actually pretty
simple. We will just add the following code to our module:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
  def self.included(base_class)
    base_class.extend(ClassMethods)
  end
```
:::

Altogether, this code would look like the following:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module HelperMethods
  def self.included(base_class)
    puts "#{base_class} has included HelperMethods. We're also going to extend ClassMethods into it as well"
    base_class.extend(ClassMethods)
  end
  def to_hash
    formatted_class_attributes = self.class.attributes_for_json.map{|attr| "@#{attr}".to_sym}
    filtered_ivars = self.instance_variables & formatted_class_attributes
    filtered_ivars.inject({}) do |map, iv|
        map[iv] = self.instance_variable_get(iv) 
        map
  end
 end
module ClassMethods
  def attributes_for_json
    [:name, :email]
  end
end
end
```
:::

Now, when our `User`{.literal} class includes the
`HelperMethods`{.literal} module and completes its class loading, the
`included`{.literal} callback will be called and the calling class
(`User`{.literal}) will be passed as an argument. The `User`{.literal}
class constant will then be sent `extend`{.literal} with the
`ClassMethods`{.literal} submodule passed to it:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class User
  include HelperMethods
end
```
:::

The output will be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer273 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.9: Output for the User class
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.9: Output for the User class

As you can see, the `included`{.literal} callback is called, and we then
extend `ClassMethods`{.literal} into the `User`{.literal} class. We can
infer the following points:

-   This is a simple example, but this paradigm provides the basis to
    leverage some powerful features of Ruby to write useful modules that
    add diverse functionality to lots of different classes.
-   We are calling the `ClassMethods`{.literal} submodule due to common
    convention, but this is arbitrary.
-   In the preceding example, we are using `include`{.literal} as the
    entry point for the class to interact with the module, and thus we
    use the `included`{.literal} callback and call `extend`{.literal} to
    add class methods. However, module authors can do the converse by
    telling developers to use `extend`{.literal} instead, which then
    calls the `self.extended`{.literal} callback, which then calls
    `include`{.literal} on the class that did the extending. Again, the
    reason for using one approach over the other is merely convention
    and possibly for semantics, as it makes slightly more sense
    linguistically to include a module than to extend it.

[]{#_idTextAnchor186}

Enumerated Types {#_idParaDest-180}
----------------

Enumerated types are not specific to modules, but will come in handy for
the next exercise, so let\'s take a brief moment to talk about them in
Ruby. An enumerated type is a data type consisting of a set of named
values. In other words, enumerated types, or, as they are commonly
called, enums, are custom data types that consist of a set of
predefined, or enumerated values.

A common example of an enumerated type is a status. For instance, if you
have an e-commerce application, you might have an order status that is
comprised of \[`:draft`{.literal}, `:ordered`{.literal},
`:delivered`{.literal}, `:canceled`{.literal}\]. It is useful to fix
those values to an integer, although a symbol value can work just as
well. Integers are commonly used because they are performant for storing
in a database, so comparisons and queries are much faster. In Ruby,
symbols are more performant than strings, but if you had to save a
status in a database, that symbol would get converted to a string.
Therefore, it\'s good practice for enums to have integer values.

To summarize:

-   Enumerated types allow you to explicitly list the set of possible
    values that

-   can occur.

-   Enumerated types allow you to change the name at any time as long as
    the value remains the same.

-   Enumerated types are commonly referred to as enums.

    Note

    Enumerated types should not be confused with the Ruby
    `Enumerable`{.literal} module.

In practice, enumerated types rarely change, but when they do, it is
usually to add an additional type into the set of values.

Here is an example of a `PaymentTypes`{.literal} enum:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class PaymentTypes
  CREDIT_CARD = 1
  CHECK = 2
  WIRE = 3
  TYPES = [CREDIT_CARD, CHECK, WIRE]
end
```
:::

Here, we\'ve defined the possible payment types as named constants and
the named constants are assigned an integer value. We\'ve also created a
`TYPES`{.literal} constant so we can easily iterate over the possible
types that are defined.

Designing enums in this way is a bit cumbersome and is only mildly
useful. Let\'s design a module that makes working with enums far more
useful and makes it quick and easy to define classes as enums.

[]{#_idTextAnchor187}

Exercise 6.04: Writing a Module to Define Payment Methods for a Product Application {#_idParaDest-181}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we are going to write a module that defines what
payment types will be accepted at a product application store. We are
going to write a utility module, called `Enum`{.literal}, that allows
for any class to be turned into an enumerated data type. The
requirements for our module will be such that the enum classes will be
defined with a `DATA`{.literal} constant, which is an array of all the
values of our enum. Each element of the `DATA`{.literal} array will
itself be an array with the integer value, symbol, and label. This gives
us the flexibility to store the value in a database, work with it in
Ruby as a symbol, or output a human-readable label:

1.  Create a class that includes the `Enum`{.literal} module and defines
    the enum types in the `DATA`{.literal} array:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class PaymentTypes
      include Enum
      DATA = [
        [ WIRE = 1, :wire, "Wire"],
        [ CHECK = 2, :check, "Check"],
        [ CREDIT = 3, :credit, "Credit card"],  
      ]
    end
    ```
    :::

    Here, we have a basic Ruby class that includes the `Enum`{.literal}
    module (to be defined). Then, we declare a `DATA`{.literal} constant
    that has our actual `Enum`{.literal} types of `:wire`{.literal},
    `:check`{.literal}, and `:credit`{.literal} with associated values
    and labels.

2.  Build out the module with a basic `included`{.literal} callback:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module Enum
      def self.included(base_class)
        base_class.extend ClassMethods
        base_class.class_eval do 
            attr_reader :id, :name, :label
      end
    end
    module ClassMethods
    end
    end
    ```
    :::

    Here, we\'ve added some new magic. As discussed in the previous
    chapter, using the `included`{.literal} callback is a powerful
    paradigm for modules. As we\'ve seen, we first extend
    `ClassMethods`{.literal}; we\'re going to leave the
    `ClassMethods`{.literal} submodule empty for now. The next line runs
    `class_eval`{.literal} and passes a block to it.

    `class_eval`{.literal} is a special Ruby method that will run the
    code contained in the preceding block in the context of the class
    definition. Running `attr_reader`{.literal} in the
    `class_eval`{.literal} block is the same as if we called it normally
    in a basic class definition. So, essentially, we are just adding
    reader methods on whatever class includes `Enum`{.literal} for
    `:id`{.literal}, `:name`{.literal}, and `:label`{.literal}.

3.  Add a constructor to the module:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module Enum
    # ... omitted for brevity
      def initialize(id, name, label=nil)
        @id = id
        @name = name
        @label = label
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    This is a basic constructor and uses the basic `include`{.literal}
    module principles we learned at the beginning of the chapter. The
    `initialize`{.literal} method will be added to all instances of the
    class that include `Enum`{.literal}.

4.  Test out the instantiation:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    pt = PaymentType.new(1, :wire, "Wire")
    pt.id
    pt.name
    pt.label 
    ```
    :::

    The output would be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer274 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.10: Output for payment details
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

    Figure 6.10: Output for payment details

    Okay, so we can see our module is basically working. We properly
    extended the class with the `attr_reader`{.literal} method and our
    constructor was added as well. However, we can also do something
    weird, such as this:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    pt = PaymentTypes.new(nil, :foo, "Huh?")
    ```
    :::

    On the console, it would look as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer275 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.11: Payment type details
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

    Figure 6.11: Payment type details

    We just created a weird payment type that isn\'t really an
    enumerable that we expect. We could add a validation to the
    constructor, but we\'ll leave that as an exercise for you, dear
    reader.

5.  Add a `ClassMethod`{.literal} module to get all the types:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module ClassMethods
      def all
        @all ||= begin
            self::DATA.map { |args| new(*args) }
        end
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    Here, we\'ve defined an `all`{.literal} class method that loops over
    the `DATA`{.literal} constants, instantiates each one and assigns it
    to a class instance variable. Let\'s test it out:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    PaymentTypes.all
    ```
    :::

    The output would be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer276 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.12: Output for all payment types
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

    Figure 6.12: Output for all payment types

    Isn\'t this amazing? We wrote a module that allows us to easily
    define enums as an array in any class. Our module adds an
    `all`{.literal} method that returns all of the types for us as
    instances of objects. When we started with enums, they were just
    integers stored in constants. But now with our module, they are
    instances of objects and we have all the power of object-oriented
    programming behind us to work with these types.

6.  Add some instance methods to `PaymentTypes`{.literal}:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class PaymentTypes
      include Enum
      DATA = [
        [ WIRE = 1, :wire, "Wire"],
        [ CHECK = 2, :check, "Check"],
        [ CREDIT = 3, :credit, "Credit card"],  
      ]
      def wire?
        id == WIRE
      end
      def check?
        id == CHECK
      end
      def credit?
        id == CREDIT
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    We\'ve added some methods here. These methods are called
    `interrogation`{.literal} methods because they ask the instances
    what they are. Is it a wire? Is it a credit card? Because our enum
    is a plain old Ruby class, we have full flexibility for the behavior
    of this type.

    If we were to create more and more enums, the chances are high that
    we would also create interrogation methods on each of those types.
    Can we write code in our module that automatically creates those
    interrogation methods for us? If you\'ve been paying attention, then
    you\'ll know the answer is yes. There are a few approaches here, but
    we\'ll use our old friend `method_missing`{.literal} from the
    previous chapter.

7.  Respond to interrogation methods using `method_missing`{.literal}:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module Enum
      def is_type?(type)
        name.to_sym == type.to_sym
      end
      def method_missing(method, *args, &block)
        interrogation_methods = self.class.all.map{|type| "#{type.name}?".to_sym}
        if interrogation_methods.include?(method)
            type = method.to_s.gsub("?", '').to_sym
            is_type?(type)
        else
            super
        end
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    Great, so we added a `is_type?`{.literal} method, which is our
    comparison method. We overrode `method_missing`{.literal} to check
    whether the missing method that was called was an interrogation
    method to a valid type, and if so, formatted it and passed it to the
    `is_type?`{.literal} method:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    PaymentTypes.all[0].wire?
    PaymentTypes.all[0].credit?
    PaymentTypes.all[2].wire?
    PaymentTypes.all[2].credit?
    ```
    :::

    The output would be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer277 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.13: Output for checking the payment type
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

Figure 6.13: Output for checking the payment type

Now we get these interrogator methods for free with any enum class that
includes our module. This module is quite often used in production
applications, although it contains quite a few more utility methods.


Module Methods {#_idParaDest-182}
==============

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
As we\'ve learned so far, modules have primarily been used to add
instance or class methods to other classes. You can add instance or
class methods depending on whether you `include`{.literal} or
`extend`{.literal} that module into your class. In both cases, though,
the methods to be added are always defined as basic methods. This is in
contrast to class methods in a class definition, which have the
`self.`{.literal} prefix for their declaration.

However, we also saw that the module callbacks were declared differently
using the `self.`{.literal} prefix. Let\'s see what happens if we define
other methods using the `self.`{.literal} prefix on a module like so:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module BabelFish
  def self.the_answer
    return 42
  end
end
```
:::

What we\'re doing here is defining static module methods. These are very
similar to class methods but on a module. They don\'t contain any state.
They are called straight onto the module constant itself:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
irb(main):058:0> BabelFish.the_answer
=> 42
```
:::

So, module methods are pretty straightforward. Here are a few modules
that are defined in the Ruby Core and Standard libraries that have
module methods:

-   The `URI`{.literal} module:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    irb(main):061:0> URI.parse("https://google.com")
    => #<URI::HTTPS https://google.com> 
    ```
    :::

-   The `FileTest`{.literal} module:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    irb(main):003:0> FileTest.directory?("specs")
    => false
    ```
    :::

-   The `Math`{.literal} module:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    irb(main):005:0> Math.atan(45)
    => 1.5485777614681775
    ```
    :::

    Note

    You can explore more modules by going to the Ruby documentation
    here: <https://packt.live/2M6n8MM>. Modules have an \"M\" next to
    them.


Namespaces {#_idParaDest-183}
==========

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
In addition to adding methods to classes and providing out-of-the-box
functionality as part of the module, another major purpose of modules is
to provide a namespace. A namespace is just what it sounds like: it
provides a scope or space for naming. In particular, it provides a space
for constants. With the exception of raw global methods, the entry point
for most code will be through a constant, whether it be a class constant
or a module constant.

We\'ve learned how to create classes and modules. Really, what we are
doing is creating constants that point to those objects in memory. When
we create constants (classes, modules, or otherwise) in IRB, we are
creating a constant in the global namespace. This can quickly get
crowded, especially if you are creating a class or module constant that
may have a common name.

For instance, in the previous topic, we created an `Enum`{.literal}
module. `Enum`{.literal} is a very common word in the Ruby world, and do
we really think our `Enum`{.literal} module is the best and that we
should own that word? It is possible there is a more official
`Enum`{.literal} library, or that Ruby may use it as a global constant
in the future. Therefore, it\'s a good practice to name your global
constants with a name that is more unique. By doing this, you are also
declaring a unique namespace that you can then put other constants
inside of to make them safe from name collision.

As such, let\'s rename our `Enum`{.literal} module to be a bit more
specific to what the module

is doing:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module ActsAsEnum
end
class PaymentTypes
  include ActsAsEnum
end
```
:::

The name `ActsAsEnum`{.literal} is not very inspired, but it is
descriptive and as such makes it easy to read and understand what might
be happening. While `ActsAsEnum`{.literal} is more unique than
`Enum`{.literal}, in the Ruby world, lots of people use the
`ActsAs`{.literal} convention, so this may still have issues. We\'ll go
with it for now.

Now that we\'ve defined our `ActsAsEnum`{.literal} module, assuming
it\'s unique, we are free to add constants inside the `module`{.literal}
namespace and we can be sure to avoid name conflicts. In fact, we can
use modules for no other purpose than to define namespaces:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module Zippy
  SKIPPY = "skippy"
  class Zappy
end
module Dappy
  def self.say_something
    puts "doo"
  end 
end
end 
```
:::

We defined our arbitrary namespace, `Zippy`{.literal}, and created the
`Skippy`{.literal}, `Zappy`{.literal}, and `Dappy`{.literal} classes. If
we need to access the classes within the namespace, we use the scoping
operator, `::`{.literal}, as follows:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
Zippy::SKIPPY
Zippy::Zappy.new
Zippy::Dappy.say_something
```
:::

The output would be something as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer278 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.14: Output after using the scoping operator
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.14: Output after using the scoping operator

We can see that it doesn\'t matter whether we\'re accessing a constant
with all caps, a class constant, or a module constant -- we still use
the `::`{.literal} scoping operator to access it.

Ruby is pretty smart about its constant lookup, but sometimes it can get
confused, or sometimes you have to override its lookup behavior. The
following exercise will show you the problem and provide you with a
solution.

[]{#_idTextAnchor190}

Exercise 6.05: How to Reuse Constants with a Namespace {#_idParaDest-184}
------------------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we will be reusing the global `User`{.literal}
constants. We will be using the global scoping operator for this
purpose:

1.  Write a global class constant that is also a constant inside a
    module:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class User
      def self.output
        return "Global User"
      end
    end
    module Report
      def self.test_namespace
        User.output
      end
      class User
        def self.output
            return "Report::User"
        end
      end
    end
    ```
    :::

    Here, we\'ve got two classes with the commonly labeled
    `User`{.literal} constant. However, the second `User`{.literal}
    class is present within the `Report`{.literal} module namespace.

2.  Call the `Report`{.literal} module of the `test`{.literal} method:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    Report.test_namespace
    ```
    :::

    The output will be returned as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer279 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.15: Output after applying the namespace method
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

    Figure 6.15: Output after applying the namespace method

    This is as expected. You would expect to call `User`{.literal},
    which is inside the module, to be called by the module itself. What
    if we want the global `User`{.literal} constant, though?

3.  Add a method to access the global constant from inside the
    `module`{.literal} namespace:

    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class User
      def self.output
        return "Global User"
      end
    end
    module Report
      def self.test_namespace
        User.output
      end
      def self.test_global
        ::User.output
      end
    class User
      def self.output
        return "Report::User"
      end
    end
    end
    ```
    :::

    We\'ve added a `test_global`{.literal} module method that references
    the global `User`{.literal} constant by using the scoping operator,
    `::`{.literal}, but without anything before it. This is the global
    scoping operator. The output would now be as follows:

    ::: {#_idContainer280 .IMG---Figure}
    ![Figure 6.16: Output for the test\_global module
    ](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
    :::

Figure 6.16: Output for the test\_global module

We have thus reused the `User`{.literal} global constant as a common
constant for all methods.


prepend {#_idParaDest-185}
=======

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
So far, we\'ve discussed the `include`{.literal}, `extend`{.literal},
and `module`{.literal} methods and namespaces. There is one more aspect
to modules that came with the Ruby 2.0 release several years ago:
`prepend`{.literal}. `prepend`{.literal} is not often used, perhaps
because it is not well understood. Let\'s change that.

First, let\'s consider the following example:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module ClassLogger
  def log(msg)
    "[#{self.class}] #{msg}"
  end
end
class User
  include ClassLogger
  def log(msg)
    "[#{Time.now.to_f.to_s}] #{super(msg)}"
  end
end
class Company
  prepend ClassLogger
  def log(msg)
    "[#{Time.now.to_f.to_s}] #{super(msg)}"
  end 
end
```
:::

We\'ve created a module called `ClassLogger`{.literal}, which implements
a `log`{.literal} method. This method wraps a string and outputs the
current class. We\'ve also created two classes, `Company`{.literal} and
`User`{.literal}, which implement an identical `log`{.literal} method
that first calls `super`{.literal} with the `msg`{.literal} argument,
then adds a prefix of the current time to the log message.

The difference is that `User`{.literal} calls `include`{.literal} to
this module, whereas `Company`{.literal} calls `prepend`{.literal}:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
User.new.log("hi")
Company.new.log("hi")
```
:::

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer281 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.17: Output after prepend
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.17: Output after prepend

The `User`{.literal} implementation (`include`{.literal}) got both the
`time`{.literal} and `class`{.literal} prefixes, whereas
`Company`{.literal} only has the `time`{.literal} prefix. What\'s going
on here? The answer lies in how Ruby dispatches methods, as shown in the
following code:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
User.ancestors
```
:::

The `ancestors`{.literal} method output for the `User`{.literal} class
will be displayed as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer282 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.18: The ancestor output for the User class
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.18: The ancestor output for the User class

Similarly, the `ancestors`{.literal} for the `Company`{.literal} class
will be:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
Company.ancestors
```
:::

<div>

::: {#_idContainer283 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.19: The ancestor methods for the Company class
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.19: The ancestor methods for the Company class

We call the `ancestors`{.literal} method, which is an introspection
method Ruby provides us with on class objects. We can see a significant
difference here. The `User`{.literal} class ancestors have
`User`{.literal} first and then `ClassLogger`{.literal} second. The
`Company`{.literal} class has `ClassLogger`{.literal} first and then
`Company`{.literal} second. As such, Ruby calls methods from each of
these classes in this hierarchy in that order. The
`ClassLogger`{.literal} implementation doesn\'t call `super`{.literal},
so the chain stops there, which is why we only see that particular
output. When `User`{.literal} calls `log`{.literal}, it first calls the
`User`{.literal} implementation (the `time`{.literal} prefix) and then
calls `super`{.literal}, which then calls the `ClassLogger`{.literal}
implementation. This is why we see the string output with
`time`{.literal} first and then `class`{.literal} second.

When we started this chapter, we said that calling `include`{.literal}
was essentially like copying and pasting the code into the class. This
isn\'t entirely true. As we can see, what\'s actually happening is that
it\'s being added into the class hierarchy in an ordered fashion. That
is, it adds the methods to the class hierarchy after the class itself.
`prepend`{.literal}, on the other hand, is adding to the class hierarchy
before the class itself.

Prepending methods to the class hierarchy gives rise to some very
important behaviors. Primarily, it allows modules to have their methods
called first. By being called first, modules then have complete control
of the original implementation. They can preprocess or postprocess data
and behavior. Module authors should dutifully call `super`{.literal} to
make sure that the original implementation is called or have a good
reason to not do it.

[]{#_idTextAnchor192}

prepend with Subclasses {#_idParaDest-186}
-----------------------

We\'ve said that `prepend`{.literal} adds module methods to the top of
the class hierarchy. However, what happens when we subclass a class that
has prepended a module? First, let\'s look at the subclass hierarchy in
the following code:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class ParentClass
end
class ChildClass < ParentClass
end
ParentClass.ancestors
```
:::

The ancestors for `ParentClass`{.literal} will be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer284 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.20: The ancestor method output for ParentClass
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.20: The ancestor method output for ParentClass

Similarly, the output for `ChildClass`{.literal} will be as follows:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
ChildClass.ancestors
```
:::

<div>

::: {#_idContainer285 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.21: The ancestor method output for ChildClass
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.21: The ancestor method output for ChildClass

This makes sense. The child class is higher up in the class hierarchy
than `ParentClass`{.literal}, which is what explains basic inheritance
behavior in Ruby. Now add a module to prepend, as shown in the following
code:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
module PrependedModule
  def output
    puts "Outputting from the PrependedModule"
    super
  end
end
class ParentClass
  prepend PrependedModule
  def output
    puts "Outputting from the parent class"
  end
end
class ChildClass < ParentClass
  def output
    puts "Outputting from the child class"
  end
end
ChildClass.new.output
```
:::

`ChildClass`{.literal} will now look as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer286 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.22: ChildClass
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.22: ChildClass

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
ChildClass.ancestors
```
:::

The `ancestors`{.literal} method on `ChildClass`{.literal} will respond
as follows

<div>

::: {#_idContainer287 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.23: The ancestor method output for prepended ChildClass
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.23: The ancestor method output for prepended ChildClass

Similarly, for `ParentClass`{.literal}, the `ancestors`{.literal} method
will respond as follows:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
ParentClass.ancestors
```
:::

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer288 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.24: The ancestor method output for prepended ParentClass
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.24: The ancestor method output for prepended ParentClass

As we can see, `ChildClass`{.literal} appears higher up in the hierarchy
than the prepended module. This means the module\'s function will not be
called unless `ChildClass`{.literal} calls `super`{.literal}, as shown
in the following code:

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
class ChildClass < ParentClass
  def output
    super
    puts "Outputting from the child class"
  end
end
puts ChildClass.new.output
```
:::

The output would now be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer289 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.25: Output for the prepended module
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.25: Output for the prepended module

If we want our module to work for subclasses too, we have another Ruby
callback: `inherited`{.literal}. Consider the following code:

inheritedcallback.rb

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
1  module PrependedModule
2  
3   def output
4    puts "Outputting from the PrependedModule"
5    super
6   end
7  end
8  
9  class ParentClass
10  prepend PrependedModule
11 
12  def self.inherited(klass)
13   klass.send(:prepend, PrependedModule)
14  end
15 
```
:::

<https://packt.live/2IH18pl>

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer290 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.26: Output for the inherited callback
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.26: Output for the inherited callback

This type of coding is very advanced, and care should be taken to make
sure that the method chain is understood well. In other words, take care
to understand how `super`{.literal} is placed in the method chain so
that the module method is not called multiple times if that is not
desired.

The preceding code still requires `ParentClass`{.literal} to define the
`inherited`{.literal} callback. We can go even further with our module
with the following code:

inheritedcallback\_withparentclass.rb

::: {.informalexample}
::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
Copy
:::

``` {.language-markup}
1  module PrependedModule
2   def output
3    puts "Outputting from the PrependedModule"
4    super
5   end
6   def self.prepended(base_class)
7    puts "Included: #{base_class}"
8    base_class.instance_eval do
9     def self.inherited(klass)
10     puts "Inherited: #{klass}"
11     klass.send(:prepend, PrependedModule)
12    end
13   end
14  end
15 end
```
:::

<https://packt.live/2VDaTKz>

The output would be as follows:

<div>

::: {#_idContainer291 .IMG---Figure}
![Figure 6.27: Using the prepended module
](data:application/octet-stream;base64,)
:::

</div>

Figure 6.27: Using the pre[]{#_idTextAnchor193}pended module

Here, we have done some really advanced Ruby coding by using the
prepended callback to know when our module was prepended. We also use
`instance_eval`{.literal} to evaluate a block of code in the context of
the class constant instance. This allows us to dynamically define the
inherited callback method, which then allows us to prepend our module on
the subclass.

--------------------------------------------

In this exercise, we will prepend `ApplicationDebugger`{.literal} to the
`Application`{.literal} class and define the `debug`{.literal} function,
which takes `application_name`{.literal} and debugs the application:

1.  Create a new Ruby file, `Exercise6.06.rb`{.literal}.
2.  Define the `ApplicationDebugger`{.literal} module with the
    `debug`{.literal} function:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    module ApplicationDebugger
      def debug(args)
        puts "Application debug start: #{args.inspect}"
        result = super
        puts "Application debug finished: #{result}" 
      end
    end
    ```
    :::
3.  Define the `Application`{.literal} class:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    class Application
      prepend ApplicationDebugger
      def debug(args)
        {result: "ok"}
      end
    end
    ```
    :::
4.  Add the invocation code:
    ::: {.informalexample}
    ::: {.toolbar .clearfix}
    Copy
    :::

    ``` {.language-markup}
    DBugger = Application.new
    DBugger.debug("NotePad")
    ```

Summary {#_idParaDest-189}
=======

::: {#_idContainer294 .Content}
This chapter aimed to provide you with the knowledge necessary to create
modules with the Ruby object model. We have added instance methods by
including modules into classes. We have added class methods to extend
class functionality. We have created namespaces for our modules. As a
very crucial part, we have made a distinction between prepending modules
into classes and how you can extend and include functionality. Modules
in Ruby accomplish multiple purposes such as creating namespaces,
creating reusable class and instance methods, and modifying a class\'s
code at runtime. Modules are Ruby\'s answer to multiple inheritance, in
that they allow classes to incorporate code from multiple sources. As we
saw in the last section, when a module is included or prepended, it
affects the class hierarchy, which is what Ruby uses to do method lookup
and dispatch. The ordering of this hierarchy is important and something
to keep in mind as you start using third-party modules in your
application code.

Now that we\'ve covered all the major fundamentals in Ruby, in the next
chapter, we\'ll use what we have learned to focus on importing data from
external sources, processing it using the models we\'ll create, and
outputting that data in a common format such as CSV.
